    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "On 11 February 2020 the World Health Organisation declared the COVID-19 outbreak a pandemic and since then there has been a race against the clock to readjust healthcare systems, to limit the spread, to find a treatment or to develop a vaccine.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Hospitals have reorganised their activity in order to protect healthcare providers and have suspended elective cases. Guidelines prioritizing vascular intervention during the outbreak were elaborated by the scientific societies 1, 2, 3.Many scientific societies have elaborated guides to prioritize vascular intervention during the outbreak.1, 2, 3\n",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 228,
                    "end": 229,
                    "mention": "1",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 231,
                    "end": 232,
                    "mention": "2",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 234,
                    "end": 235,
                    "mention": "3",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                },
                {
                    "start": 341,
                    "end": 342,
                    "mention": "1",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 344,
                    "end": 345,
                    "mention": "2",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 347,
                    "end": 348,
                    "mention": "3",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "In a recent letter to editor, JJ Ng et al4 showed that more than 90% of the vascular units had suspended or scaled down elective cases.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 41,
                    "end": 42,
                    "mention": "4",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Our department reduced the medical staff to the minimum necessary to perform emergency interventions and all other procedures were cancelled after careful revision.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Here, we present our point of view regarding the preparation needed of a vascular unit for the end of COVID-19 crisis. The extrapolation can help other units to find the best way to organise and to foresee upcoming events.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Aorta. For EVAR and TEVAR preparation is needed re-evaluate the cases that are fit for outpatient procedures5 and re-evaluate the priority according to the risk of rupture and the need of post-procedural intensive care. For FEVAR procedures and other custom-made prostheses that are already manufactured, attention must be paid to ensure that CT scans are not older than 6 months.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 108,
                    "end": 109,
                    "mention": "5",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Carotid. An ultrasound exam must be provided followed by a medical visit after the lockdown is lifted, in order to confirm permeability, mostly for tight lesions, to ensure usual follow-up and to prepare the further interventions if necessary6.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 242,
                    "end": 243,
                    "mention": "6",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Iliac arteries and peripheral artery disease. Most of these patients can be treated as outpatient procedures, but care must be taken to identify the patient at risk of complications. In order to plan interventions for PAD patients, pre-operatory exams must be scheduled: US exams to evaluate the permeability, venous cartography for bypasses and angiography for BTK pathologies7. The necessity of balloon and stents will increase after the end of the outbreak and device companys may not be able to keep up with orders",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 377,
                    "end": 378,
                    "mention": "7",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Haemodialysis accesses. Most haemodialysis access were not postponed but other patients will need follow-up and re-interventions and must be considered in the future operating schedule.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Clinical trials. Most clinical trials were temporarily stopped and follow-up visits must be organised as soon as possible.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "General consideration. The use of operating theatres must be prepared in conjunction with other surgical units. For inpatient capacity, a network of rehabilitation centres, home-care nurses and telemedicine8 must be organized to ensure an optimal in-flow and out-flow of patients. Vascular patients must not become collateral damage of COVID-19, continuity of follow-up is key. The current crysis is unexpected and unique and we need to find solutions, be innovative and to hope for the best and prepare for the worst.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 206,
                    "end": 207,
                    "mention": "8",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF7"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        }
    ],
